<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-849-036  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 849 036.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Design  Oct 16 1989 v28 n20 p29(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Standards prompt short-haul fiberoptic applications.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Martin, S. Louis.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Evolving fiber optic communications standards and productdevelopment agreements between vendors are enabling thedevelopment of fiber optic technologies for both short- andlong-haul communications applications.andP;  The Fiber Channel standardfor input-output management is nearing completion, while fivestandards incorporated in the Fiber Distributed Data Interface(FDDI) are compatible with Open Systems Interconnection (OSI)model layers, and two more (the physical and data link layers) arebeing written.andP;  The Fiber Channel standard's completion isenabling manufacturers to develop compatible integrated circuits.andO;Two physical media dependent documents (for single and multimodefiber) define the FDDI physical layer and consequent fiberimplementations.andP;  ATandamp;T, Hewlett-Packard, and Siemens AG haveagreed to a pin-for-pin compatible FDDI transceiver standard.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber OpticsOptical CommunicationsStandardsFiber Distributed Data Interface StandardSystem Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphphotograph.andO;Caption:   Component cost per fiber meter. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>